t is relevant to issues in food security. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="INTRODUCTION"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">INTRODUCTI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ON</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Research Councils UK (RCUK</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) is a strategic partnership set up to champion the research supported by the seven UK Research Councils. RCUK was established to enable the Councils to work together more effectively to enhance the overall impact and effecti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">veness of their research, training and innovation activities, and contributing to the delivery of the Government’s objectives for science and innovation. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:0.03pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This response is submitted by RCUK on behalf of the following research councils:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 41.81pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Biotechnology and B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iological Sciences Research Council (BBSRC)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 41.81pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Economic and Social Research Council (ESRC)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 41.81pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council (EPSRC)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 41.81pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Medical Research Council (MRC)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 41.81pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Natural Environment Research Council (NERC)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 41.81pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Science and Technology Facilities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Council (STFC)</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RCUK welcomes the opportunity to provide evidence to the Committee. This response focuses only on those issues raised by the committee that are rele</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vant to RCUK or the individual c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ouncils that have contributed to the response. It also provides some more generic briefing that is relevant to the overall subject of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nquiry, and which the Committee may wish to consider.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RCUK submitted evidence to the Committee’s last inquiry on thi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s topic in 2009. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BBSRC and several research council institutes and centres submitted separate evidence that supplemented the RCUK submission. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Further detail was also provided in supplementary evidence via the Government Chief </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scientific</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Advisor. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Much of the material in those submissions remains pertinent. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some of the material included in this response may have also been included in written submissions to other parliamentary inquiries in the area of food security, to which the Research Councils h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ave responded, for example the recent House of Commons International Development Committee Inquiry on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Global Food Security (2012/13)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><a name="GENERAL_BRIEFING"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">GENERAL BRIEFING</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Food security is underpinned by food production systems – a chain of activities from production, proces</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sing, packaging, transport to trade and retailing. RCUK activities contribute to understanding throughout </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">these</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">interaction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with and impact</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the wider environment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> societal needs, and economic conditions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK food security </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">canno</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t be considered in isolation from its global context since </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">supplies are partly dependent on imports (wholly dependent for some foods).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Food security is distinct from self-sufficiency: increasing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> national</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> self-sufficiency for a particular food does not necessarily mean improved security</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of supply</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, since UK production </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and supply chains </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">may</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be vulnerable to disruption, for example by adverse weather, pests or disease. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Food security </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">discussions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> often focus </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on land</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-based</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> production system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owever</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as 30% of the world’s animal protein production is derived from fisheries, the issues of security cannot be divorced from the sustainable management of wild </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stocks.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><a name="Global_Food_Security_programme"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Global Food Security programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> committee’s 2009 inquiry, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> significant development in the coordination of UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">food </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">research has been the establishment of the Global Food Security programme (GFS). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK’s main public sector funders</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of food-related research and training have joined forces to develop, design and implement a programme to coordinate research and associated activity. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Global Food Security Strategic Plan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> 2011-2016</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> represents a single shared high-level strategy across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all programme partners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and has been recently refreshed</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Collectively, GFS partners spend around £</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">350M </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">per year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">directly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on food-related research.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">They </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support a large portfolio of research </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> underpins food security, including plant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">animal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and microbia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">biology, biodiversity and the provision of ecosystem services, climate and weather modelling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, engineering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and food manufacturing, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and economic and social science relevant to the production, supply and consumption of food</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For further information on the G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">FS programme see </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Annex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="RESPONSES_TO_ISSUES_RAISED"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">RESPONSES TO ISSUES RAISED BY THE COMMITTEE</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="How_best_to_improve_UK_food_sec"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How best to improve UK (and EU) food security, including using resources more efficiently</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Through the GFS programme and other funding mechanisms, RCUK supports </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a wide range of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">research relevant to this issue (and others raised by the com</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mittee)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Research is needed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on both supply and demand sides</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, including issues such as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> food </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">production, markets and trade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">food safety and nutrition; dietary choice, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consumer behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">food w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aste;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">resilience of soils, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">crop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and livestock</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nitrogen management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> understanding of the relationship between agriculture and the wider environment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">biodiversity, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">climate and weather) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to address</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the need for sustainable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">intensification</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of agriculture</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#00ff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Substantial programmes of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">research relevant to food security, including research on resource use, take place at the institutes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and centre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that receive strategic funding from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Research Councils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(see </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Annex 2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ome examp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">les of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RCUK-supported </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">research </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at these and other establishments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are given below; further detail on these and other research can be supplied if required.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he 20:20 wheat® project at Rothamsted Research</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> aims to increase potential wheat yields in the UK to 20 tonnes per hectare within the next 20 years. The project is seeking ways to improve the quantity and quality of wheat, for example through genetic improvement, improved photosynthetic efficiency, alt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ered plant structures, modified seed development and more efficien</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> use of nutrients. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#00ff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Biodiversity and Ecosystem Service Sustainability (BESS) programme</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, funded by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NERC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, seeks to understand biodiversity within landscape</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> where food </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">production</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to be balanced with the provision of other ecosystem services, against the backdrop of climate change. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Recognising the actual or potential degradation of agricultural landscapes has consequences for their biodiversity and the provisioning and resilience of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> services.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ecosystem Services for Poverty Alleviation (ESPA) is a £40.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> programme</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> co-funded by DFID, NERC and ESRC. Within this programme, the research conducted by the ASSETS consortium will increase understanding of how dynamic stocks and flows of ecosystem services translate to local-level food security and nutritional health. ESPA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has a global perspective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> looking at the sustainability impact of agricultural expansion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on ecosystem services in areas such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bolivia, Malawi and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Yangtze basin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The work of the International Nitrogen Initiative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> chaired by the NERC Centre for Ecology and Hydrology </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(NERC-CEH)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aims to bring together the issues of too much and too little nitrogen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, examining how improving efficiency of nitrogen flow in the economy can contribute simultaneously to managing global</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> food security and environmental security.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Initial outcomes have been highlighted in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Our Nutrient World</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> report commissioned by UNEP</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Sustainable Land Use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> science area at the NERC-CEH has a strong focus on agr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-ecosystems and aims to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">develop and t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">est practical and economically viable management systems that actively protect, restore, enhance and optimise the ecosystem functions that are integral to food production. Research includes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">increasing the resilience </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agro-ecosystems to environmental </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">threats and stressors, including eutrophication, climate change and habitat fragmentation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as well as work to protect and enhance the ecosystem functions required for crop production (e.g. pollination, pest control, nutrient cycling). This science area is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">complement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Soil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">programme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">whose aim is to deliver integrated solutions for understanding, measuring, mapping, managing and conserving both pristine and managed soils.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Rural Economy and Land Use programme (RELU)</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">included a project that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">develo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ped the use of scenarios</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for future change in the uplands</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> found that a policy of increasing UK self-sufficiency would lead to more intensive management of uplands, with negative impacts on ecological balance, flood risk, river quality and the capacity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for peat to store carbon. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ESRC has co-funded research with Defra and the Scottish Government that explored the potential for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">changing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> eating habits</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to improve UK food security and sustainability, which found that large and/or permanent changes in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">diets</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are rare, because these are tied up with other related habits</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and cultural conventions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">those around eating and shopping.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ESRC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">funded research highlighted the potential contribution to UK food security that alternative food systems that champion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local food can play, and both the importance and diversity of “food hubs</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">” – intermediaries that link local producers with consumers – and “creative procurement” by large organisations, in supporting local food.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Reducing food waste could make a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">substantial contribution to improving food security.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A recent report</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for the GFS programme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">identified key challenges and research priorities to reduce food waste and losses across the whole supply chain. </span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><a name="relationship_between_price_and_cost"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The relationship between the price of food and the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> cost of producing it</span></a></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">achieve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> food security there is a need to understand </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">better and quantify </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the costs to the wider environment of agricultur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e and food systems</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Such costs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are external to the main economic activity and may be highly dispersed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> comprehensive assessment of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">values to people of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">services provided by ecosystems </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">requires </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">linking </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">them to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> human well-being. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To deliver a better understanding of the complexities of the natural environment in valuation analyses and to consider the wider societal value of ecosystem services, NERC is leading </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">thcoming </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Valuing Nature</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">research </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">programme.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><a name="implications_of_volatility"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">implications of vo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">latility in global food supply and demand </span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">for UK food security</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ESRC-funded researchers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contributed to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2009 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Chatham House report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Food Futures: Rethinking UK Strategy</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which highlighted the dependence of UK food security on global supply chains. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the UK was greater hit by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">global </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">food price inflation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in 2008</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> than many similar developed nations. Food price volatility is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> caused by multiple drivers, and is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> not just affected by global food yields</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Furthermore, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overall </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">figures for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> self-s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ufficiency hide the fact that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK is highly reliant on non-EU sources for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">certain key products such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fruit, soya products and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">phosphate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fertilisers.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he report recommend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that UK food security is not developed in isolation from the European and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">loba</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l contexts within which it operates.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><a name="contribution_science_and_GM"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The potential value and contribution of science and GM</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> technology to UK food security</span></a></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Science and technology offer the potential for advances in many aspects of UK and global food security</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> including the sustainability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of food production, supply and consumption. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government’s Agri-Tech strategy (published July 2013) aims to improve the translation of current and new research into practical application on the farm and elsewhere in the supply chain, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the concept of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sustainable intensification</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of agriculture as a central theme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. RCUK welcomes this strategy and BBSRC in particular is working closely with others including government and industry to implement it. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">GM is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">just </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">one technology among many that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have the poten</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tial to benefit UK food security</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">M is an essential tool for modern bioscience research.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pecific commercial applications of research should be assessed on a case by case basis. For GM crops this includes, for example, consideration of the nature of the t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ransferred trait, the crop species and its potential for out-crossing and other environmental impacts, as well as wider social issues such as the nature of benefit(s) offered by the crop, and the benefits and costs to different sectors of society, as well </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as broader technical, political, economic and social factors.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Through the introduction to commercial crops of gene</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from related or other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">species)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that confer naturally-occurring resistance to pests or pathogens, GM may offer scope for more environmental</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ly-benign alternatives to the repeated application of pesticides. BBSRC has supported research on the development of potatoes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">resistant to nematode worms or potato blight</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fungus, and of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wheat that repels aphids</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. GM may also have the potential to increase </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agricultural productivity through reduction of animal disease, for example by preventing the transmission of avian influenza</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Further potential applications include enhancing the nutritional content of foods. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The potential for agricultural innovation to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contribute to food security and nutritional value is not limited to GM technologies. For example, other innovations arising from RELU-research that could benefit UK food security include using UV-transparent plastic film in polytunnels to enhance the flavo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">noid and antioxidant capacity of vegetables</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; and grazing sheep on biodiverse pastures to improve the fatty acid profile in lamb</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. However, there are trade-offs between food quantity, nutritional quality and environmental protection; both these example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sult</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in lower yields compared to conventional agricultural practice.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#00ffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ESRC-funded research</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has found that biosafety regulations developed in response to local settings and demands better incorporate diverse views to assure trust and accountability. Rese</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">arch on participation in biotechnology has found that for controversial new technologies such as GM, deliberation can provide a space for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">alternative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> views and solutions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> when</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> designed in such a w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ay that powerful voices do not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">take over the debate, and impl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">emented early in the decision-making </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">process to ensure that citizen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">help to shape</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the process. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">STFC provides large</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">scale scientific infrastructure for the use of the wider UK research community. These facilities are used in research relevant to food</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> security issues, for example, the use of the Central Laser Facility’s OCTOPUS</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cluster in crop resilience research</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the design and build of instruments used in earth observation e.g. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">monitor rainforest clearance</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NERC-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CEH </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s also investing in la</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rge-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">scale infrastructure that is relevant to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">food security through the installation of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">COSMOS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (COsmic-ray Soil Moisture Observing System</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) at sites across the country. Sensors </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">detect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cosmic-ray neutrons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and hence measure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> average soil water content over </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a footprint of ~30 hectares. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This system provides </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">soil moisture </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">data at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> an intermediate scale between point sensors and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">estimates from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> remote sensing technologies.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><a name="increased_resilience"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How food and farming supply chains, and the current systems for traceability, can contribute</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to increased resilience</span></a></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The structure of food supply chains has important implications for food security, and research is increasingly addressing the whole supply chain “from farm to fork” by, for example, demonstrating that a focus on “food miles” can b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e an unhelpful simplification</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ESRC-funded research has demonstrated that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> innovation and new technology in supply chains is delivering efficiency improvements and sensitivity to market conditions. However, it can also drive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an increase</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">imp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ort of produc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ts and inputs from outside the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">K</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The wider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> global food system is prone to periodic scares and crises, not just around food availability and price volatility but also food safety.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The ESRC and Food Standards Agency have jointly launched, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">under the auspices of the Global Food Security programme,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an initiative to fund research into risks to food safety</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><a name="climate_change"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Whether climate change risks are adequately incorporated in UK food security strategies and planning</span></a></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is important to incorporate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">resilience into food supply systems</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> including to climate change and severe weather events. Severe weather has an immediate impact on food production and transport, directly affecting livelihoods through changes in accessibility and affordability. Wider en</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vironmental resilience is equally important in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">soil, water supply, nutrients and land use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. As well as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">better forecasting there is a need for better </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">integration of weather</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> information</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, farm management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> logistics </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to improve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> resilience at multiple scales f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rom field to globe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Climate change brings about long</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">term variation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the potential to grow crops, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">but also more significant short-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">term impacts through severe weather. Impacts will be on yield, quality and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">productivity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(crop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, livestock and fisheries), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">resilience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and logistics. The impacts of severe weather are also influenced by the landscape and how it is managed, for example deforestation can increase the risk of soil erosion and landslides during periods of intense rainfall.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NERC research centres</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ERC-CEH </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the National Oceanography Centre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are investigating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the effects of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">atmospheric pollution on food security and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">climate change on marine and freshwater food sources. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Several</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the world’s most important staple food crops </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(especially </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wheat and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> soybean</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> but also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rice, maize and potato</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are sensitive to ground-level ozone pollution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with yield</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> being reduced. For the UK, adverse economic impacts are the greatest for wheat</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The most vulnerable regions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the UK are the main crop growing areas of c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">entral England and East Anglia. Complex interactions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">exist </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">between air pollution and climate change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with ozone pollution modifying the responses of crops to other environmental stresses such as drought and pests and diseases.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#00ff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Plymouth Marine Laboratory </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has investigated the impacts of climate c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hange on global fish production by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">integrating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> climate change projections, ecosystem models and fisheries </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">data</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The results</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> indicate that, despite human population growth, current levels of fish consumption (18 kg </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">per capita per year) are sustainable in 2050 provided that global fisheries operate within maximum sustainable yields, and that the aquaculture industry increases its efficiency to reduce the amount of fishmeal required.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NERC Centres </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> data (at a va</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">riety of spatial and temporal levels) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> many national and international assessments including the IPCC and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> working with the Met</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rological Office to increase understanding of underlying processes that will themselves directly impact on agriculture.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Increased capability to do impact assessments for both short term and longer term weather through improved models and landscape</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">scale monitoring systems will facilitate predictive capability. NERC centres have a long history in this area, and the Environme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ntal Virtual Observatory</span><a name="_ftnref26"></a><a href="#_ftn26">[26]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is a good example of how big data sets can now be modelled through cloud</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">based architecture to understand potential impacts on food security. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ESRC-funded research</span><a name="_ftnref27"></a><a href="#_ftn27">[27]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has highlighted the need to think about whole food systems, not just agricultural production, when considering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">resilience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to global environmental </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">change. Other components of the food system, such as road and rail freight and food storage, can also be vulnerable to climate change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> impacts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and innovation to build resilience is needed in all food system components.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><a name="obstacles_production_markets"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The obstacle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s facing food producers, including small farmers, seeking to increase production and access new markets</span></a></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government policy seeks to encourage farmers to increase the resilience of their livelihoods by diversification into new markets. Diversification strat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">egies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in their effectiveness. RELU research has demonstrated a range of benefits for tilapia </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fish-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">farming as a diversification strategy for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">livestock and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">arable farmers</span><a name="_ftnref28"></a><a href="#_ftn28">[28]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. However, ESRC-funded BRASS research</span><a name="_ftnref29"></a><a href="#_ftn29">[29]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has shown that there is room for far greate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r innovation in government policies to promote multi-functional farming.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Other policies are drivers for change in the agricultural economy, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">raising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> potential barriers to agricultural development. For example, RELU research</span><a name="_ftnref30"></a><a href="#_ftn30">[30]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> showed the UK’s nutritional pol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">icy, which encourages the reduction in animal-derived saturated fat consumption and an increase in the consumption of fruit and vegetables, could change </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rural land use and the rural economy, including increasing unemployment, and boosting horticulture i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">outh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ast </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at the expense of livestock production areas.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="increasing_self_sufficiency"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ways of increasing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">self-sufficiency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> in products for which the UK has a comparative advantage</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:1.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The analysis of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Our Nutrient World</span><a name="_ftnref31"></a><a href="#_ftn31">[31]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> demonstrated how nutrient efficiency of the overall food chain links technical measures in agriculture and food supply to consumer choices. Reducing excessive consumption of meat and dairy products, while ensuring that dietary requirements are met, shows </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">potential to both complement and stimulate actions within the agricultural sector. Such behavioural changes could contribute substantially to reducing the current requirement for feed and food imports, while stimulating the market for high quality meat and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> dairy products, with reduced environmental burden.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">December 2013</span></p></div><br style="clear:both; mso-break-type:section-break; page-break-before:always" /><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ANNEX </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="ANNEX_1_GFS"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Global Food Security programme</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.47pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Under the Global</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Food Security programme (GFS) the UK’s main public sector funders of food-related research and training have joined forces to develop, design and implement a programme to coordinate research and associated activity. The programme partners are Research Cou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ncils UK, BIS, Defra, DFID, DH, FSA, GO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, Scottish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government, Welsh Government and the Technology Strategy Board, with the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Wellcome Trust, STFC and the Met Office as observers. Collectively, GFS partners spend around £</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">35</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">0M per year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">directly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on food-related research. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.47pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Global Food Security Strategic Plan, 2011-2016</span><a name="_ftnref32"></a><a href="#_ftn32">[32]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> represents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a single shared high-level strategy across all programme partners.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It has been updated as of November 2013 to reflect the latest research and programme developments.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.47pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The GFS programme uses the UN FAO definition of food security</span><a name="_ftnref33"></a><a href="#_ftn33">[33]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Food security exists when all people, at all times, have physical and economic access to sufficient, safe and nutritious food to meet their dietary needs and food preferences for an active </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">and healthy life</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.” This implicitly includes future generations, and requires food production methodologies to be sustainable.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.47pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The programme is intended to help meet the global challenge of providing the world’s growing population with a sustainable and se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cure supply of safe, nutritious and affordable high quality food. That food will need to be produced and supplied from less land and with lower inputs, and in the context of global climate change, other environmental changes and declining resources. The pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ogramme has three cross-disciplinary research themes, based on those set out in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">UK Cross-Government Food Research and Innovation Strategy</span><a name="_ftnref34"></a><a href="#_ftn34">[34]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.61pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Resilience </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.61pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sustainable production and supply</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.61pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Nutrition, health and wellbeing</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.47pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Due to the scope, complexity and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inter-related nature of challenges, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he GFS programme takes interdisciplinary and whole systems approaches to research on UK and global food systems. This research considers both supply and demand, and is coupled with its effective translation into practic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e and policy. The scope of the programme includes: food production and resource management; food economics, markets and trade; food processing, manufacture and distribution systems; food safety and nutrition; consumption habits and practices; and waste in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the food system.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The programme aims to provide evidence to enable food producers and processors, retailers, consumers and government to respond to and manage the challenges facing the UK food system and related global issues, including the many challenges </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">confronting the developing world in the face of environmental and demographic change.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 17.47pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A number of publications have helped inform the drivers and challenges addressed by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Foresight report</span><a name="_ftnref35"></a><a href="#_ftn35">[35]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The Future of Food and Farming</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (201</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ANNEX </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="ANNEX_2_CENTRES_INSTITUTES"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">RESEARCH COUNCIL C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">TRES AND INSTITUTES</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> RELEVANT TO FOOD SECURITY</span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BBSRC provides strategic funding to the following institutes</span><a name="_ftnref36"></a><a href="#_ftn36">[36]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> relevant to food security</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Institute of Biological, Environm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ental and Rural Sciences (IBERS,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Aberystwyth University</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Institute of Food Research</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">John Innes Centre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Pirbright Institute</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Roslin Institute (University of Edinburgh) </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Rothamsted Research</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Genome Analysis Centre</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Of the research programmes supported by EPSRC, those most relev</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ant to food security are:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">EPSRC Centre for Innovative Manufacturing in Food</span><a name="_ftnref37"></a><a href="#_ftn37">[37]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RCUK Centre for Sustainable Energy Use in Food Chains</span><a name="_ftnref38"></a><a href="#_ftn38">[38]</a></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">research </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">centres</span><a name="_ftnref39"></a><a href="#_ftn39">[39]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and their delivery partners </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">supported by NERC, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">those most relevant to food security are:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Centre </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for Ecology and Hydrolo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">National Oceanography Centre</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">National </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Centre for Atmospheric Science</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Plymouth Marine Laboratory</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scottish Association for Marine Science</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Further details are available at </span><a href="http://www.rcuk.ac.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">www.rcuk.ac.uk</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> The programme partners are Research Councils UK, BIS, Defra, DFID, DH, FSA, Scottish Government, Welsh Government and the Technology Strategy Board, with the Wellcome Trust and the Met Office as observers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a href="http://www.foodsecurity.ac.uk/assets/pdfs/gfs-strategic-plan.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">www.foodsecurity.ac.uk/assets/pdfs/gfs-strategic-plan.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a